<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4532&amp;p=39591#p39591</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4532&amp;p=39591#p39591"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Best way to open famicom cart without an axe (...)]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4532&amp;p=39591#p39591"><![CDATA[
I've never actually looked at a Famicon cart closely, so I have no firsthand experience, but I googled really quick and found this:<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://detail.chiebukuro.yahoo.co.jp/qa/question_detail/q116990246">http://detail.chiebukuro.yahoo.co.jp/qa ... q116990246</a><!-- m --><br /><br />He says to take a tiny flathead screwdriver and slip it into the seam on the side of the cart.  When you have pried it open a little bit, stick another thin-bladed tool in there to prop it open (freeing your flathead screwdriver).  Then, with your tiny flathead screwdriver, "move, wait, pry".  As you do this, the crack will gradually get bigger (presumably you'd do this all the way around the cart?  though he doesn't say this specifically).  Do this carefully over and over and eventually you'll get it open.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3632">MetalSlime</a> — Wed Nov 05, 2008 5:45 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
